The extent and frequency of coral bleaching events have increased in recent years (
Hughes et al. , 2018a
), resulting in coral mortality and coral populations lacking time to recover between bleaching events (
Hughes et al. , 2017
). Reef-associated species are consequently vulnerable, with their disappearance potentially resulting in ecosystem restructuring (
Hughes et al. , 2018b
;
Stuart-Smith et al ., 2018
). The Great Barrier Reef (GBR) has been seriously affected by recent bleaching events, with an estimated 91% of reefs suffering from bleaching and a loss of 30% of live coral cover (
Stuart-Smith et al., 2018
), leading to a phase shift from hard coral to an algal-dominated system. Herbivory is thought not only to enhance reef resilience to phase shifts but also to assist reef recovery by reducing macroalgal biomass that could otherwise smother the corals ( Kuempel & Altieri, 2017 ; Spadaro & Butler, 2021 ), and even open up spaces on which coral larvae can settle (
Webster et al. , 2015
)

Understanding the roles that different species play in reef ecosystems is important, not only to determine their potential role in coral reef resilience, but also their fate should coral reefs bleach and not recover (

Stella 
et al.,
2011

; 

Bravo 
et al.,
2021

). Coral reef grazers have different impacts on the ecosystem depending on their distribution, biomass, size, and functional role (
Mumby, 2006
; 
Kuempel & Altieri, 2017
; 

Altman-Kurosaki 
et al
., 2018

). Grazing by herbivorous fishes is often considered a key driver of coral reef biodiversity and resilience (

Mumby 
et al
., 2016

) and it has even been shown that species of cryptic fishes can represent an important component of the total biomass of grazing fishes (
Townsend & Tibbetts, 2004
).

Fishes are nevertheless not the only herbivores active in reef systems. Turtles (

Wabnitz 
et al
., 2010

), sea urchins (
Hughes, 1994
), large brachyuran crabs (
Spadaro & Butler, 2021
), and even small invertebrates (
Carpenter, 1997
) can also regulate algal communities. These small invertebrates have the potential to influence the density and assemblage structure of different species of macroalgae (

Bellgrove 
et al
., 2014

), and can access spaces and microhabitats that larger species cannot, but their role in controlling algal recruitment and abundance is seldom considered.

Typically defined as small herbivores (i.e., <
2.5 cm
), mesograzers such as amphipods, gastropods, small crabs and shrimps can reach densities that have the potential to alter the biomass of epiphytes and algae on coral reefs, particularly in the absence of the larger macrograzers (
Brawley & Adey, 1981
; 
Ruesink, 2000
; 

Altman-Kurosaki 
et al.,
2018

).

Among the diversity of reef mesograzers, hermit crabs have received little attention. It is thought that some species may contribute to ecosystem functioning through grazing (
Pearson et al., 2018
) or through the use of mollusc shells that would otherwise have been buried by sediments, promoting shell turnover (
Gutiérrez et al. , 2003
), which in turn can sustain a new community of epibiotic and endolithic species ( Williams & McDermott, 2004 ).

The remaining 41 coral fragments covered with dead and epilithic algae were also put in individual plastic containers to serve as controls to determine the quantity of detritus and faeces (potentially from boring fauna) attributable to the presence of hermit crabs. Estimates of the levels of chlorophyll at the end of the experiment were made by using a stainless-steel spatula to scrape 4 × 1 cm 2 of epilithic algae and any associated detritus from the 82 coral fragments. The material removed was placed on a GF/C filter paper (Whatman™, Springfield Mill, UK ). Each filter paper was placed inside a vial with a 10 ml solution of 9:1 acetone/water to extract chlorophyll and then refrigerated in the dark at 4 ºC for 24 hours. The solution was filtered once again to remove any detritus. Three aliquots of 200 µl of the solution were then analysed using a spectrophotometer (model UV-1700, Shimadzu, Kyoto , Japan ) and read at wavelengths of 630 nm , 647 nm and 664 nm , the peak absorption wavelengths for chlorophyll c2 and c1, chlorophyll b and chlorophyll a, respectively (
Larkum et al ., 2012
).

The detritus from both the control and experimental containers was filtered, at the end of the 72 h, using a vacuum pump filtering system and GF/C filters (Whatman™). The filters had been pre-labelled with unique numbers using a pencil and their weight subsequently measured (± 0.01 g ) in a low-humidity, acclimatised environment using a top loading balance. The process was repeated for the 82 samples after which each filter paper was folded twice to secure the sediments within and placed in an oven at 60 ºC for 24 h (following
Christiansen et al ., 2010
). The weight of the filter paper with the detritus was measured and the original weight of the filter paper was subtracted to determine the weight of the detritus. This was then placed in a vial with 10 ml of 9:1 acetone water solution to extract chlorophyll and refrigerated in the dark at 4 ºC for 24 h. The solution was once again filtered to remove any detritus and three replicates of 200 µl of the filtrate were analysed using a spectrophotometer at wavelengths of 630 nm , 647 nm , and 664 nm . The chlorophyll concentration in milligrams per gram was then calculated with the aforementioned equation replacing the “scraped surface area” with “detritus weight.”

Generalised linear models (GLM) were used to test for differences in the amount of chlorophyll present in the coral fragments, amount of chlorophyll in the detritus, and amount of organic biomass between the two treatments. The differences in weight of the crabs before and after the treatment was computed using a paired samples Wilcoxon test after checking for normality using a Shapiro-Wilk test. All statistical analyses were performed using R (R 
Core Team, 2019
). Starting levels of chlorophyll and organic biomass were not measured due to the potential effects from handling.

Many brachyuran crabs have generally been recognised as ecosystem engineers due to their capacity to modify habitats (
Bertness, 1985
; 
Stachowicz & Hay, 1999
; 

Munday 
et al
., 2004

; 

Cannicci 
et al
., 2008

; 
Glynn & Enochs, 2011
). Historically the role of hermit crabs (Anomura) in ecosystem engineering has been mostly attributed to their ability to recycle gastropod shells (
Williams & McDermott, 2004
), but there are studies that highlight the potential of hermit crabs to actively graze on epilithic algae (

Benvenuto 
et al
., 2003

; 
Tran, 2014
), which can aid in the regulation of particular algal communities (
Ruesink, 2000
; 

Altman-Kurosaki 
et al.
2018

) or even in maintaining coral reef health (

Pearson 
et al.,
2018

). Reef-dwelling hermit crabs can reduce the amount of algae growing on corals (
Coen, 1988
) and are able to feed on them when many other herbivorous species are not due to the toxic compounds that some algal species possess that affect most fauna (
Hay & Fenical, 1988
), but not some species of brachyuran crab (
Stachowicz & Hay, 1999
).

was based on both the observed behaviour of the hermit crabs and the amount of chlorophyll removed from the corals under the experimental condition in comparison to controls (
Fig. 1A
). Levels of chlorophyll in the detritus also validated this finding, with chlorophyll in the detritus under the experimental set-up having higher levels than that in the control setting. Detritus that accumulated during the experiment, which was protected from the hermit crabs but was possibly increased as a consequence of their active grazing, may include fragments of algae dislodged by crabs, undigested material in their faeces as well as algal growth due to nutrients and carbon dioxide excreted by the crabs, which could help explain the significantly higher amount of chlorophyll (
Fig. 1B
). The fact that organic biomass was also lower in the experimental condition is concurrent with the crabs being mesograzers and feeding on epilithic algae, since this difference in the detritus is most likely a consequence of absorption of organic matter and expelling inorganic matter in the faeces (
Fig. 1C
).
